 =20

Ten days ago OpenAI was worth $86 billion. Investors in OpenAI were about t=
o launch a tender offer to buy employee shares at that valuation, and emplo=
yees were lining up to tender; there were willing buyers and sellers at tha=
t price. Then events occurred. There was a boardroom coup, and OpenAI=E2=80=
=99s founder and chief executive officer, Sam Altman, was fired. At one poi=
nt, the valuation of OpenAI was apparently=C2=A0zero dollars:=C2=A0Several =
OpenAI investors were noisily saying that they were going to   write down t=
heir shares to zero,
  [1]
 and it looked like Microsoft Corp. was about to  acquire most of OpenAI=E2=
=80=99s staff=C2=A0without paying the company (or its other investors) anyt=
hing for them.
But then there was another boardroom coup, Altman   got his job back, and m=
ost of the directors who fired him were themselves fired. Altman returned, =
and there have been suggestions that he=C2=A0(and Microsoft, OpenAI=E2=80=
=99s biggest investor) extracted some promises=C2=A0that this sort of thing=
 won=E2=80=99t be allowed to happen again, that there will be fundamental g=
overnance changes to make OpenAI more robust and, probably, more commercial=
.=C2=A0
So how much should OpenAI be worth=C2=A0today?=C2=A0Some possible answers:
=09Less than $86 billion, for governance reasons: After a rapid rise in pro=
minence and valuation, OpenAI revealed some serious cracks,=C2=A0causing it=
s valuation to become zero dollars for a while, meaning that investors shou=
ld be far more cautious about it now than they were before. It is more vola=
tile than people thought. The lesson of the last week, I  suggested on Tues=
day, might be =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t invest in nonprofits at an $86 billion=
 valuation=E2=80=9D; maybe investors will learn that lesson.=C2=A0=09More t=
han $86 billion, for governance reasons: Those cracks were there from the b=
eginning, and investors presumably accounted for them in that $86 billion v=
aluation. But now that Altman has won his power struggle and  cemented his =
control, the future OpenAI  will be=C2=A0less=C2=A0weird and nonprofit-y an=
d afraid of its own shadow. It=E2=80=99s the same exciting business but wit=
h better, more investor-friendly governance, so it should be worth more to =
investors.=09Less than $86 billion, for governance reasons (2): Did=C2=A0Al=
tman win his power struggle? Ten days ago, he was the CEO and a board membe=
r; now he is off the board. Ben Thompson quotes a  Reddit post arguing that=
 the drama was precipitated by Altman=E2=80=99s=C2=A0efforts to seize total=
 control of the board, and that the other board members outmaneuvered him, =
with the result that his power has been diminished. The other board members=
 =E2=80=9Cget the outcome they want: Sam and Greg [Brockman] gone from the =
board; Adam [D=E2=80=99Angelo] remains, who has experience of Sam and Greg=
=E2=80=99s shenanigans; and two mutually agreeable independent board member=
s are added=E2=80=9D who will presumably rein in Altman.=09More than $86 bi=
llion, for governance reasons (2): Maybe a board that reins in Altman will =
start by reining in his   extracurricular AI-related business ventures (a c=
hip company, =E2=80=9Can AI-focused hardware device=E2=80=9D) and make him =
focus more on OpenAI, which will be good for the company. =E2=80=9CWhen Alt=
man returns, he=E2=80=99ll likely have to address claims that he=E2=80=99s =
been distracted by a number of projects, including those outside OpenAI,=E2=
=80=9D  reports the Information. Maybe he=E2=80=99ll do the hardware stuff =
within OpenAI instead of in a new startup, creating more value for OpenAI i=
nvestors.=09Less than $86 billion, for straightforward business reasons: Th=
e instability of the last week was bad for customers, who will be reluctant=
 to base their AI strategies on OpenAI and will shift to its competitors.  =
Thompson writes: =E2=80=9CAny company would have to think long and hard abo=
ut basing their business on OpenAI=E2=80=99s API.=E2=80=9D=09More than $86 =
billion, for business reasons: This last week sure drew a lot of=C2=A0atten=
tion=C2=A0to OpenAI and its products and their capabilities, and if you thi=
nk of OpenAI as basically a consumer internet company then any attention is=
 good. If you read a week of press about how OpenAI=E2=80=99s board members=
 are afraid that its product will enslave humanity, I mean, that is kind of=
 good advertising for the capabilities of that product?=09More than $86 bil=
lion, for technological reasons.=C2=A0One precipitating event of the boardr=
oom coup might have been a breakthrough in OpenAI=E2=80=99s research. Reute=
rs  reported=C2=A0that =E2=80=9Cseveral staff researchers wrote a letter to=
 the board of directors warning of a powerful artificial intelligence disco=
very that they said could threaten humanity,=E2=80=9D and the Information  =
reported=C2=A0that this was =E2=80=9Can innovation by the company=E2=80=99s=
 researchers earlier this year that would allow them to develop far more po=
werful artificial intelligence models,=E2=80=9D including a model called Q*=
 that=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cwas able to solve math problems that it hadn=E2=80=99t =
seen before.=E2=80=9D If you were willing to buy OpenAI stock at an $86 bil=
lion valuation as a bet that it would develop increasingly powerful AI mode=
ls, evidence that it has in fact developed increasingly powerful AI models =
should cause you to increase your valuation.
  [2]

=09Less than $86 billion, for regulatory reasons: All this drama is going t=
o increase regulatory attention on AI, and new rules will make it harder fo=
r OpenAI to innovate and commercialize rapidly.=09More than $86 billion, fo=
r regulatory reasons:=C2=A0All this drama is going to increase regulatory a=
ttention on AI, and new rules will make it harder for OpenAI=E2=80=99s=C2=
=A0smaller competitors=C2=A0to innovate and commercialize rapidly, leaving =
it with a head start on building=C2=A0a monopoly.=09Precisely $86 billion: =
Nothing worth thinking about=C2=A0happened over the last 10 days.

I think that last answer is obviously insane but I am not a venture capital=
ist! We talk a lot around here, in a semi-joking way,=C2=A0about this   app=
ealing feature=C2=A0of private market investments: They are less volatile t=
han public investments, because when dramatic shifts in markets or fundamen=
tals happen,=C2=A0you can ignore them=C2=A0and just say that the value of y=
