order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;"> The Information reported last week</a>:</=
p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">An OpenAI employee share sale that values the =
firm at $86 billion is back on track following Sam Altman=E2=80=99s reinsta=
tement as CEO late Tuesday night, a person familiar with the matter said. T=
he deal, in which a group of investors led by Thrive Capital will buy up to=
 $1 billion of stock=E2=80=94and conceivably more=E2=80=94held by employees=
 or other investors, is expected to close next month. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a statement, a spokesperson for the Josh Ku=
shner=E2=80=93run Thrive said they were impressed by the =E2=80=9Cresilienc=
e and strength=E2=80=9D they witnessed over the last few days and that they=
 =E2=80=9Cconsider it a true honor to be their partners now and in the futu=
re.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Though the Financial Times <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33498739.286429/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY=
29tL2NvbnRlbnQvYzRkZDJlYzAtMDI2Zi00NWRkLWE3ZDQtZDdhYWE1Y2Y5Mzk2/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cBa33f9cfe" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targ=
et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;"> is less confident</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">An upcoming sale of shares in OpenAI is set to=
 test how much the past week=E2=80=99s leadership chaos has cost the compan=
y and its backers, though big investors are bullish about securing a high v=
aluation.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The employee stock sale, which had been planne=
d before the sacking last week of chief executive Sam Altman and expected t=
o value the company at $86bn, will continue as planned, according to two in=
vestors with direct knowledge of the matter.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Investors remain confident that a new share sa=
le can still treble the $29bn valuation placed on OpenAI when Microsoft com=
mitted to invest $10bn in the company at the start of this year.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CClearly this almost destroyed a lot o=
f value in the short term, it=E2=80=99s hard to say what happens next,=E2=
=80=9D said Vinod Khosla, an early investor in OpenAI. =E2=80=9CValuation i=
s a function of investor perceptions. The company is the same or better off=
 than it was last Thursday.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But analysts have suggested that OpenAI will b=
e hit by the week=E2=80=99s events, with rival groups such as Google and Am=
azon representing strong and stable challengers in the race to offer genera=
tive artificial intelligence services to businesses and consumers.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know that there are still will=
ing buyers and willing sellers at that $86 billion price, or that there are=
 as many of them as there were 10 days ago, but it seems like there might b=
e. Doesn=E2=80=99t someone have to be wrong? I suppose it is possible that =
the answer is =E2=80=9Cthe distribution of possible OpenAI outcomes is much=
 wider than it was 10 days ago, but the midpoint of that distribution is st=
ill $86 billion,=E2=80=9D but what a weird coincidence that would be.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Actually another possible answer is that the d=
istribution of outcomes is=C2=A0<em>narrower=C2=A0</em>than it used to be. =
Like, 10 days ago:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">I suppose it was=C2=A0possible that A=
ltman would come to the board and say =E2=80=9Cthis nonprofit stuff isn=E2=
=80=99t working, we need to fire you and become a regular for-profit startu=
p.=E2=80=9D I mean,=C2=A0OpenAI used to be=C2=A0<em>entirely=C2=A0</em>a no=
nprofit, and now it is a hybrid nonprofit/capped-profit entity, and you mig=
ht have expected it to continue to move in that direction.</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Conversely, it was totally possible that the nonpr=
ofit board would fire Altman and burn the company to the ground in order to=
 prevent it from developing unsafe artificial intelligence. (=E2=80=9CAllow=
ing the company to be destroyed =E2=80=98would be consistent with the missi=
on,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
ick/33498739.286429/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYXhpb3MuY29tLzIwMjMvMTEvMjAvb3BlbmFpLXN=
0YWZmLWxldHRlci1ib2FyZC1yZXNpZ24tc2FtLWFsdG1hbg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1a=
7eaaa1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;"> a board member apparently told employees</a>.)</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then these last 10 days have cut off some =
of those possibilities. The first possibility =E2=80=94=C2=A0OpenAI becomes=
 purely for-profit =E2=80=94=C2=A0I guess is still open, but it might be le=
ss likely, given the fierce resistance the old board put up and the fact th=
at that board still has a representative on the new board. Altman =E2=80=9C=
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33498739.286429/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTEtMjIvc2FtLWFsd=
G1hbi10by1yZXR1cm4tYXMtb3BlbmFpLWNlby13aXRoLWEtbmV3LWJvYXJkP2NtcGlkPUJCRDEx=
MjcyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV=
0bV90ZXJtPTIzMTEyNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cC51bdf4bb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;">also agreed</a> to an internal investigation into the c=
onduct that led to his dismissal,=E2=80=9D which suggests that there will s=
till be a counterbalance to his power in the new company, and limits on his=
 ability to do, uh, whatever that conduct was.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The second possibility =E2=80=94=C2=A0burn the=
 company to the ground, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0seems much less likely now. The=
=C2=A0board <em>did</em> fire Altman, and it almost burned the company to t=
he ground, and then the board blinked, and presumably the new board (and an=
y future board)=C2=A0<em>won=E2=80=99t do that again</em>. Like, they tried=
 that, they saw what happened, they didn=E2=80=99t like it,=C2=A0lessons ha=
ve been learned, and that is no longer an option for the board.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so for instance consider Microsoft Corp., =
which has committed some $13 billion to OpenAI and relies on its products f=
or its AI strategy. One possible conclusion for Microsoft to draw from this=
 drama would be =E2=80=9Cwe need much more robust legal protections, and a =
board seat, so that this doesn=E2=80=99t happen again.=E2=80=9D But another=
 possible conclusion would be =E2=80=9Cactually no, it turns out we have pl=
enty of leverage already, we got what we wanted after a few tense days, so =
we don=E2=80=99t need a board seat after all.=E2=80=9D The Wall Street Jour=
nal <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33498739.28642=
9/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS90ZWNoL2FpL3NhdHlhLW5hZGVsbGEtbWljcm9zb2Z0LWNlb=
y1haS1vcGVuYWktYWx0bWFuLTg1ZTc1NTMxP21vZD1ocF9sZWFkX3BvczI/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cB786c1b01" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;"> reported last week</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Even after investing $13 billion, Microsoft di=
dn=E2=80=99t have a board seat or visibility into OpenAI=E2=80=99s governan=
ce, since it worried that having too much sway would alarm increasingly agg=
ressive regulators. That left Microsoft exposed to the risks of OpenAI=E2=
=80=99s curious structure. Altman=E2=80=99s company was set up as a nonprof=
it with a board whose primary responsibility wasn=E2=80=99t maximizing shar=
eholder value but developing safe AI =E2=80=9Cthat benefits all of humanity=
.=E2=80=9D By not having a board seat, Microsoft ended up blindsided. The c=
ompany was also vulnerable to Altman leaving to start another company and t=
aking employees with him=E2=80=94or, in a possibility that seemed remote un=
til suddenly it was reality, OpenAI=E2=80=99s board firing him without aski=
ng for input from its biggest investor. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Microsoft has had to strike a tricky balance w=
ith OpenAI: safeguarding its investment while ensuring that its ownership s=
take remained below 50% to avoid regulatory pitfalls.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And there were moments last week when it looke=
d like Microsoft had gotten that balance wrong, and its investment might be=
 worthless. But not too many of them? The worst case seems to have been mos=
tly =E2=80=9CMicrosoft hires Altman and all of his employees and has basica=
lly acquired OpenAI for=C2=A0$13 billion=E2=80=9D; the best case=C2=A0=E2=
=80=94 and largely=C2=A0the actual outcome =E2=80=94=C2=A0was =E2=80=9CMicr=
osoft can tell OpenAI=E2=80=99s board what to do even without having a boar=
d seat.=E2=80=9D No board seats and tons of practical leverage is probably =
better, for economic and regulatory reasons, than having a board seat. And =
now everyone knows!</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Last Monday, I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/33498739.286429/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvb=
S9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTEtMjAvd2hvLWNvbnRyb2xzLW9wZW5haT9jbXBpZD1C=
QkQxMTI3MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHR=
lciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzExMjcmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a3=
19a23cBb8195787" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_=
blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;">  wrote a column</a> the gist of which is =E2=80=
=9Csure the nonprofit OpenAI board technically controls the company and Mic=
rosoft and the other investors have no legal rights, but practically the in=
vestors have the money=C2=A0and they will probably get what they want.=E2=
=80=9D I qualified that conclusion,=C2=A0because at the time the investors =
conspicuously had not gotten what they wanted, but by Tuesday night they di=
d. It turns out that Microsoft=E2=80=99s informal sources of leverage were =
in fact good enough. It turns out that, in exactly the right circumstances,=
 investing $13 billion in a nonprofit at an $86 billion valuation is fine.<=
/p>
